11012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111012"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman undergoes an emergency laparotomy for perforated diverticular disease. She has localised peritonitis and a Hartmann\u0027s procedure (sigmoid colectomy, end-colostomy and mucous fistula) is performed. She makes good progress for the first three days, but becomes confused, disorientated and noisy early into the fourth day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 130/94 mmHg, pulse 100/min, temperature 37.2C and oxygen saturation 96% on room air. The rest of the examination is unremarkable and her abdomen appears to be soft and the surgical sites intact and healthy-looking. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer haematological and biochemical screens earlier that day showed normal results. A chest X-ray and an ECG are both normal. She has resumed oral fluids and previously reported her pain had been well-controlled. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Give 10 mg of diazepam orally","Administer 2mg of intravenous diazepam","Start an intravenous infusion of heminevrin","Contact a relative to come in and sit with the patient","Nurse separately in a well-lit room"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDelirium is a sudden change in thinking and/or behaviour. One of the commonest causes in the older population is hospitalisation and in particular, the immediate postoperative environment. Postoperative confusion (delirium) is a common sequelae after surgical events, particularly major procedures in elderly patients. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first step in the management of such patients is to exclude any organic and treatable cause for the confusion. This might be a chest or urinary infection, current medications or drug withdrawal or an electrolyte disturbance. Once this has been done and any abnormalities corrected, other means of countering the confusion can be considered. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETaking a patient out of their own familiar environment and routine can be disturbing for them and  confusion is a common consequence of this disorientation.\u00a0Simple measures to help restore orientation such as providing human contact and \u003Cstrong\u003Elighting the room\u003C/strong\u003E may be all that is necessary to restore calm. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf that does not work, some form of sedative or hypnotic (either \u003Cstrong\u003E10mg of oral diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E, or \u003Cstrong\u003E2mg of intravenous diazepam \u003C/strong\u003Eif the patient is unable or unwilling to tolerate oral intake) may be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Econtacting a relative to come and sit with the patient\u003C/strong\u003E may help allay the patient\u0027s disorientation, finding a relative to come in at short notice is not always practical. It is usually easiest to make local arrangements such as improving the room lighting and nursing in a separate room to avoid disturbing others.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst some form of sedation (perhaps comprising a \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous heminevrin\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Einfusion\u003C/strong\u003E) may be eventually needed, particularly if the patient becomes physically aggressive, these measures should take second place to re-orienting the patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Simple measures, such as keeping the patient in a well-lit room, will manage most cases of post-operative confusion."],"references":["Marcantonio ER. Delirium in Hospitalized Older Adults. N Engl J Med 2017; 377:14566-66."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93126"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"232"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93126"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-06T18:53:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-06T18:53:43+09:30","number":11,"notes":"Edited to improve question clarity.","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"232"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111012"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"7912"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"it